==English==
===Etymology===
[[Category:Greek derivations]]
A twentieth-century borrowing of [[Ancient Greek]] ''[[εμπάθεια]]'' (''empatheia''), literally ‘passion’ (formed from ''[[εν-]]'' ''en-'', ‘in, at’ + ''[[πάθος]]'' ''pathos'' ‘feeling’), coined by [[w:Rudolf Lotze|Rudolf Lotze]] to translate German ''[[Einfühlung]]''.

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
'''empathy'''

# [[sympathetic]] [[identification]] and [[understanding]] of someone else's [[feeling]]s or [[motive]]s
# the intellectual identification of the thoughts, feelings, or state of another person
# [[pity]], [[compassion]] or [[commiseration]]

